even though he used to be kind of a big deal.

02:34.400 --> 02:41.520
Henry George was born in Philadelphia on September 2, 1839, the second of 10 children.

02:41.520 --> 02:47.760
His dad, Richard George, published religious books and was a devout Episcopalian.

02:47.760 --> 02:50.480
Henry was, uh, not so much.

02:50.480 --> 02:56.640
His dad forced him to go to the Episcopal Academy, but he hated it there, eventually dropping out.

02:56.640 --> 02:59.120
That didn't mean he didn't enjoy learning, though.

02:59.120 --> 03:03.760
He convinced his dad to hire him a tutor, and he still read a bunch,

03:03.760 --> 03:07.680
and even attended lectures at the Franklin Institute.

03:07.680 --> 03:10.960
For fun, he was particularly into economics.

03:10.960 --> 03:13.600
He read Adam Smith and David Ricardo.

03:13.600 --> 03:20.400
By the time he was 15, Henry had realized his parents were barely scraping by to feed the family,

03:20.400 --> 03:24.320
and he knew if he wanted to make some money, he must go out on his own.

03:24.320 --> 03:28.160
So he traveled the world as a cabin boy on a ship,

03:28.160 --> 03:31.120
which means he basically took care of the captain's needs.

03:31.120 --> 03:33.520
He got paid $6 a month.

03:33.520 --> 03:37.120
Instead of returning to Philadelphia after he got done working at sea,

03:37.120 --> 03:40.960
he went to San Francisco to first potentially seek gold,

03:40.960 --> 03:42.320
but after that was a bust.

03:42.320 --> 03:47.520
He worked as a typesetter, a wear and a rice mill, and a farm laborer.

03:47.520 --> 03:50.880
The job he kept coming back to was typesetter, though.

03:50.880 --> 03:54.560
Unfortunately, Henry rarely made much money.

03:55.280 --> 04:06.880
When he was 21, he met Annie Fox, an orphaned immigrant from Australia,

04:06.880 --> 04:08.800
and the two fell in love.

04:08.800 --> 04:12.320
Annie's uncle, who had been her guardian after her grandma died,

04:12.320 --> 04:17.760
didn't appreciate how poor Henry was, though, and didn't approve of the relationship,

04:17.760 --> 04:19.920
but they secretly got married anyway.

04:19.920 --> 04:23.840
Despite a happy marriage, the couple did struggle financially,

04:23.840 --> 04:27.680
even though they couldn't afford to feed them, they had four kids together.

04:27.680 --> 04:31.920
Henry George Jr., who later became a United States representative

04:31.920 --> 04:37.440
and wrote a biography about his father, Richard, Jenny, and Anna.

04:37.440 --> 04:41.840
Following the birth of Richard, times were so tough for the Georges

04:41.840 --> 04:44.880
that Henry often had a beg for food.

04:44.880 --> 04:47.520
He later recalled one story, quote,

04:47.520 --> 04:51.440
I walked along the street and made up my mind to get money from the first man

04:51.440 --> 04:54.320
whose appearance might indicate that he had it to give.

04:54.320 --> 04:58.960
I stopped a man, a stranger, and told him I wanted $5.

04:58.960 --> 05:00.640
He asked what I wanted it for.

05:00.640 --> 05:05.440
I told him that my wife was confined and that I had nothing to give her to eat.

05:05.440 --> 05:06.800
He gave me the money.

05:06.800 --> 05:10.880
If he had not, I think I was desperate enough to have killed him.

05:10.880 --> 05:17.600
Things began to turn for the better when Henry realized he wanted to be a writer in 1865.

05:17.680 --> 05:23.120
By that time, he had steady printing work for the newly created San Francisco Times

05:23.120 --> 05:26.720
and began writing political editorials for local newspapers.

05:26.720 --> 05:30.160
Even though Henry never went to college and had no formal training,

05:30.160 --> 05:32.960
his editorials became quite popular.

05:32.960 --> 05:36.240
And due to this, he got promotions at the Times.

05:36.240 --> 05:39.840
By the summer of 1867, he was the managing editor.

05:39.840 --> 05:46.800
In 1868, he left the Times to become managing editor of the bigger San Francisco Chronicle.

05:46.800 --> 05:51.600
Soon after that, he wrote his most influential article up to that point called

05:51.600 --> 05:53.840
What the Railroad Will Bring Us.

05:53.840 --> 05:58.640
It was a response to the first transcontinental railroad being completed,

05:58.640 --> 06:02.800
and while most everybody was excited about it, Henry was a bit more cynical,

06:02.800 --> 06:06.000
writing that the railroad would only benefit some people.

06:06.000 --> 06:12.080
He argued the railroad would kill small towns and small businesses while propping up already

06:12.080 --> 06:15.200
great cities and already huge corporations.

06:15.200 --> 06:22.640
Keep in mind that this was in 1868, decades before the populist movement.

06:22.640 --> 06:26.080
Henry's popularity as a writer only grew after that.

06:26.080 --> 06:30.480
While he passionately called for future populist reforms like the secret ballots,

06:30.480 --> 06:34.400
public ownership of certain natural monopolies, and the right to vote for women,

06:34.400 --> 06:38.720
he also thought free trade was way better than protectionism.

06:38.720 --> 06:40.080
Very nice.

06:41.040 --> 06:44.880
And he dabbled in politics, running for the California State Assembly.

06:44.880 --> 06:50.480
But was handily defeated by the, you guessed it, railroad industry.

06:50.480 --> 06:56.160
As Henry's editorials grew more popular, his family finally got out of poverty.

06:56.160 --> 07:01.200
But Henry wouldn't constantly stop thinking about poverty for the rest of his life.

07:07.600 --> 07:13.360
He had two aha moments that are literally the reason why I am making a video about him

07:13.360 --> 07:15.360
and his ideas today.

07:15.360 --> 07:19.600
The first happened in 1868 when he traveled to New York City.

07:19.600 --> 07:24.720
He was struck by the fact that those in poverty, in such a great city with great wealth,

07:24.720 --> 07:29.840
were apparently a lot worse off than those in poverty back home in California,

07:29.840 --> 07:32.320
a place with much less development.

07:32.320 --> 07:39.920
The second aha moment happened one day in 1870 when Henry sat on his horse overlooking San Francisco Bay

07:39.920 --> 07:48.160
after a dude told him that an seemingly unimportant acre of farmland nearby would sell for $1,000.

07:48.160 --> 07:53.120
Quote, like a flash it came over me, that there was the reason of advancing poverty

07:53.120 --> 07:57.360
with advancing wealth, with the growth of population, land grows in value,

07:57.360 --> 08:01.520
and the men who work it must pay more for the privilege.

08:01.520 --> 08:06.240
Soon Henry wrote his first analysis of what he called the land question.

08:06.240 --> 08:13.440
In 1871, Henry helped found the San Francisco Daily Evening Post and he became its editor.

08:13.440 --> 08:19.760
This is when many first became exposed to his land value tax idea.

08:19.760 --> 08:27.360
However, he accumulated lots of debt with the Evening Post and his family ended up in dire poverty again.

08:27.360 --> 08:34.160
Fortunately for Henry, by 1876 he was now a minor celebrity and began giving speeches.

08:34.160 --> 08:37.760
He also still made some money as a freelancer of sorts.

08:37.760 --> 08:43.520
On September 18, 1877, he began to write his masterpiece book.

08:43.520 --> 08:48.480
The one I told you about earlier, you know, with the long title, yeah, that's the one.

08:48.480 --> 08:52.400
We'll just call it Progress and Poverty from here on out.

08:52.400 --> 09:00.000
He finished the book in March 1879 and supposedly dropped to the floor and wept like a baby after completing it.

09:00.000 --> 09:01.040
Late one night.

09:01.040 --> 09:04.960
That sounds a bit dramatic, but maybe it happened.

09:04.960 --> 09:14.000
Anyway, by this time he and his family were living in New York City and that is where Progress and Poverty got published in 1880.

09:14.000 --> 09:17.440
And keep in mind at this time, he was 40 years old.

09:17.440 --> 09:18.560
That's my age.

09:18.560 --> 09:28.720
Well, the book didn't sell that well at first, but slowly but surely, thanks to word of mouth, it began to catch on, as did Henry George's reputation.

09:28.720 --> 09:30.720
He promoted the book in Europe.

09:30.800 --> 09:36.160
Spreading his solution for eradicating poverty and reducing extreme wealth inequality.

09:36.160 --> 09:45.120
Yep, the world was learning about his single tax on the value of land to completely replace the taxes the workers paid on their income

09:45.120 --> 09:47.760
and the taxes the owners paid on their capital.

09:47.760 --> 09:48.720
Little did he know.

09:50.320 --> 09:52.000
I've written papers on Little Did He Know.

09:53.680 --> 09:56.000
I used to teach a class based on Little Did He Know.

09:56.720 --> 10:01.600
I mean, I once gave an entire seminar on Little Did He Know.

10:01.600 --> 10:12.640
That he would literally ignite a gigantic social movement that was a major catalyst of not just the populist movement, but the entire Progress-O-Vera.

10:12.640 --> 10:19.520
Progress and Poverty sold millions of copies and eventually made Henry George a household name.

10:19.520 --> 10:24.880
And apparently at the peak of the book's popularity, and I read this from many sources,

10:24.880 --> 10:28.960
Henry George was the third most famous man in the United States.

10:28.960 --> 10:32.320
Right behind Thomas Edison and Mark Twain, of course.

10:32.320 --> 10:37.440
George's idea of a single land value tax became ridiculously popular.

10:37.440 --> 10:38.960
Actually, can I jump in here?

10:38.960 --> 10:40.320
Well, of course, Mr. Clifford.

10:40.320 --> 10:41.600
Okay, great.

10:41.600 --> 10:46.080
A land value tax is more efficient than other types of taxes.

10:46.080 --> 10:47.840
Taxes influence decisions.

10:47.840 --> 10:51.360
If we tax cigarettes, that's going to decrease smoking, which is good.

10:51.360 --> 10:56.960
But if you tax things that society actually wants, that's going to decrease their consumption and production.

10:56.960 --> 11:00.240
And that leads to something that economists call deadweight loss.

11:00.240 --> 11:04.320
Inefficient markets that are not produced in the quantity that society actually wants or needs.

11:04.320 --> 11:09.200
But since the supply of land is fixed, a land tax doesn't decrease its production.

11:09.200 --> 11:11.360
It doesn't cause deadweight loss.

11:11.360 --> 11:18.800
So sales taxes and excise taxes and even income taxes and corporate taxes can slow down the economy by discouraging production.

11:18.800 --> 11:24.080
But George argued that a single land tax would actually encourage and promote economic activity

11:24.080 --> 11:28.080
by discouraging people from hoarding land or just holding it for speculation.

11:28.080 --> 11:34.640
If you own huge tracts of unimproved, valuable land, a land tax will encourage you to either improve the land

11:34.640 --> 11:39.520
or sell it to somebody else that's going to improve the land by building houses or farms or factories

11:39.520 --> 11:42.880
or something else that'll generate enough money to pay for the tax.

11:42.880 --> 11:47.040
So in the end, all that land is used extremely efficiently

11:47.120 --> 11:51.600
and the land tax means there's tax revenue for the government to provide public goods and services.

11:51.600 --> 11:55.520
And George argued that that might be enough to provide universal basic income.

11:55.520 --> 11:56.960
Well thanks Mr. Clifford.

11:56.960 --> 12:00.320
Oh hey everyone, be sure to check out his YouTube channel.

12:00.320 --> 12:06.560
